  "prompt": "How safe is Adobe Flash Player?",
  "response": "As of **December 31, 2020**, Adobe Flash Player is no longer supported by Adobe, meaning it no longer receives security updates, patches, or technical support. This makes Adobe Flash Player **extremely unsafe** to use in any capacity. Here\u2019s why:\n\n### Key Risks of Using Adobe Flash Player:\n1. **Security Vulnerabilities**:\n   - Since Flash Player is no longer updated, any existing vulnerabilities remain unpatched, making it a prime target for hackers and malware.\n   - Exploits can lead to system compromises, data theft, and ransomware attacks.\n\n2. **Outdated Technology**:\n   - Flash Player was phased out because modern web standards (like HTML5, WebGL, and WebAssembly) have replaced its functionality in a more secure and efficient way.\n\n3. **Browser Incompatibility**:\n   - Most modern browsers (e.g., Chrome, Firefox, Edge, Safari) have disabled or removed support for Flash Player entirely.\n\n4. **Malware and Exploits**:\n   - Flash Player has historically been a common attack vector for cybercriminals. Unsafe websites or malicious SWF files can easily exploit Flash vulnerabilities.\n\n### Recommendations for Safety:\n1. **Uninstall Flash Player**:\n   - Remove Adobe Flash Player from all your devices to eliminate the risk of exploitation.\n\n2. **Use Modern Alternatives**:\n   - Replace Flash-based content with HTML5 or other modern technologies. Most websites and applications have already transitioned.\n\n3. **Keep Software Updated**:\n   - Ensure your operating system, browser, and other software are up to date to minimize vulnerabilities.\n\n4. **Avoid Flash Player Archives or Old Content**:\n   - Do not download or use archived versions of Flash Player or websites that still rely on it.\n\n### Conclusion:\nAdobe Flash Player is **no longer safe** to use. Uninstall it immediately and rely on modern, secure alternatives for your web and multimedia needs.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
